Feature: CLI one-shot update
  Scenario: Running derive in a git repository updates the spec
    Given the user is in a git repository with conversation data for the current branch
    When the user runs derive
    Then the spec file at <project>/.machinen/specs/<branch>.gherkin is created or updated
    And the spec file contains Gherkin Feature blocks with Scenario entries using Given/When/Then steps
    And the file does not contain preamble or commentary outside the Gherkin structure
    And the process exits

  Scenario: Running derive with no conversation data produces no spec
    Given the user is in a git repository
    And no conversation data is available for the current branch
    When the user runs derive
    Then no spec file is created
    And the process exits

  Scenario: Running derive preserves previously captured behaviours
    Given a branch already has a spec file at <project>/.machinen/specs/<branch>.gherkin
    And new conversation messages have been recorded for that branch
    When the user runs derive
    Then the spec file is updated to reflect the new conversation content
    And previously captured behaviours that are still valid are preserved

  Scenario: Multiple conversations on the same branch are combined
    Given two or more conversations exist for the current branch
    When the user runs derive
    Then the spec update draws from all associated conversations

Feature: Reset command
  Scenario: Running derive --reset regenerates the spec from scratch
    Given a branch already has a spec file and conversations have been partially processed
    When the user runs derive --reset
    Then the existing spec file is deleted
    And a new spec is generated from all available conversation data for that branch
    And the process exits

  Scenario: Running derive --reset with no conversation data reports no data
    Given no conversations have been recorded for the current branch
    When the user runs derive --reset
    Then a message is displayed indicating no conversations were found

Feature: Watch mode
  Scenario: Running derive watch performs an initial update then watches for changes
    Given the user is in a git repository
    When the user runs derive watch
    Then an initial spec update is performed for the current branch
    And the tool begins watching for new conversation data

  Scenario: Watch mode triggers spec updates on new conversation data
    Given derive watch is running in a git repository
    When conversation data for the current branch is created or modified
    Then a spec update is triggered for the current branch after writes stabilise

  Scenario: Watch mode is scoped to the current branch
    Given derive watch is running for branch feature-x
    When conversation data arrives for a different branch
    Then no spec update is triggered for that other branch

Feature: Init command
  Scenario: Running derive init creates an empty spec file
    Given the user is in a git repository
    And no spec file exists for the current branch
    When the user runs derive init
    Then an empty spec file is created at <project>/.machinen/specs/<branch>.gherkin
    And the process exits

  Scenario: Running derive init when spec already exists does not overwrite
    Given the user is in a git repository
    And a spec file already exists for the current branch
    When the user runs derive init
    Then the existing spec file is not modified
    And a message is displayed indicating the spec already exists

  Scenario: Running derive after init uses existing spec as context
    Given the user has run derive init and manually added behaviours to the spec file
    When the user runs derive
    Then the manually seeded behaviours are used as starting context for the spec update